{
\pard\plain \s17\sa60\sb30\widctlpar\qj \fs22\cgrid {\s17\sa60\sb30\widctlpar\qj \fs22\cgrid 
Take a secret phrase and apply Shamir Secret Sharing to encode it into n secret phrases. \par
}{\s17\sa60\sb30\widctlpar\qj \fs22\cgrid 
Using Shamir Secret Sharing, a secret phrase with "nw" words can be encoded into n secret phrases, each with "nw" words as well. Before encoding, a threshold parameter t (with t<=n) is defined, so that only t shares are required for the reconstruction of the original secret. (To reconstruct the secret, use the script reconstruct.py provided in this package.)\par
{\bkmkstart AAAAAAAAAW}
{\bkmkend AAAAAAAAAW}
{{\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\adjustright \b\f1\cgrid 
Requisites
\par}
{\tc\tcl3 \v Requisites}
1) Before running this script, a dictionary of words to encode secret phrases, with the name "wordlist.txt", must be provided in the same folder as the script. This dictionary must:{
\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
Have 2^nb words, where nb is an integer (so that each word represents an nb-bit number)\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
Be a .txt file where each line has a single word.\par}
\par
This package comes pre-loaded with BIP-39's 2048-word dictionary.\par
2) The secret phrase to be shared should:{
\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
Have between 3 and 60 words.\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
Have only words that are contained in the dictionary "wordlist.txt".\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
Be written in a single line, with each word separated by only a space.\par}
\par
By default, the secret that will be encoded is read from a .txt file called "secret.txt", to be located in the same folder as this script. (The secret may also be provided right in the command line at execution\'96see below).\par}
{\bkmkstart AAAAAAAAAX}
{\bkmkend AAAAAAAAAX}
{{\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\adjustright \b\f1\cgrid 
Execution and inputs
\par}
{\tc\tcl3 \v Execution and inputs}
This script should be called from the command line, with the following mandatory inputs (flags):\par
-n: (integer) Number of shares that will be generated from the secret phrase. -t, \'96threshold: (integer) Minimum number of shares that will be required at reconstruction.\par
The following flags are optional:\par
-s, \'96secret: (string) Allows for either of the following options:{
\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
Specify the secret phrase directly on the command line.\par
\pard\plain \s120\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pndec }\ls1\adjustright \fs20\cgrid 
Specify a custom file path to a .txt file with the secret. (In either case, the secret must abide by the same format considerations stated above) -v, \'96verbose: If this flag is used, the generated shares are verbose (see "outputs" below.)\par}
\par
\par}
{\bkmkstart AAAAAAAAAY}
{\bkmkend AAAAAAAAAY}
